Microsoft Azure is a cloud computing platform developed by Microsoft that provides a wide range of services such as computing power, storage, databases, networking, analytics, and AI. Getting started with an Azure account is the first step toward leveraging cloud infrastructure for building, deploying, and managing applications.

An Azure account acts as your identity and billing unit in the Azure ecosystem. Once you sign up, you gain access to the Azure Portal, which is a web-based interface used to create and manage resources. You can also use Azure CLI, PowerShell, or APIs for automation and scripting.

A typical real-life use case is a startup building a web application. Instead of purchasing physical servers, they can create an Azure account and deploy their application using Azure App Services, store data in Azure SQL Database, and scale resources based on demand. This reduces upfront costs and allows flexible scaling.

Another example is an enterprise migrating on-premise infrastructure to the cloud. By creating Azure accounts under an organization, they can manage multiple subscriptions, control access via Azure Active Directory, and monitor costs effectively.
